Maximum entropy classification
for record linkage

Danhyang Lee Department of Information Systems, Statistics and Management Science, University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, AL, U.S.A. Li-Chun Zhang Department of Social Statistics and Demography, University of Southampton, Southampton, U.K. Statistics Norway, Oslo, Norway Department of Mathematics, University of Oslo, Oslo, Norway Jae Kwang Kim Department of Statistics, Iowa State University, Ames, IA, U.S.A.
Abstract

By record linkage one joins records residing in separate files which are believed to be related to the same entity. In this paper we approach record linkage as a classification problem, and adapt the maximum entropy classification method in machine learning to record linkage, both in the supervised and unsupervised settings of machine learning. The set of links will be chosen according to the associated uncertainty. On the one hand, our framework overcomes some persistent theoretical flaws of the classical approach pioneered by Fellegi and Sunter (1969); on the other hand, the proposed algorithm is fully automatic, unlike the classical approach that generally requires clerical review to resolve the undecided cases.


Keywords: Probabilistic linkage; Density ratio; False link; Missing match; Survey sampling

1 Introduction

Combining information from multiple sources of data is a frequently encountered problem in many disciplines. To combine information from different sources, one assumes that it is possible to identify the records associated with the same entity, which is not always the case in practice. The entity may be individual, company, crime, etc. If the data do not contain unique identification number, identifying records from the same entity becomes a challenging problem. Record linkage is the term describing the process of joining records that are believed to be related to the same entity. While record linkage may entail the linking of records within a single computer file to identify duplicate records, referred to as deduplication, we focus on linking of records across separate files.

Record linkage (RL) has been employed for several decades in survey sampling producing official statistics. In particular, linking administrative files with survey sample data can greatly improve the quality and resolution of the official statistics. As applications, Jaro (1989) and Winkler and Thibaudeau (1991) merged post-enumeration survey and census data for census coverage evaluation. Zhang and Campbell (2012) linked population census data files over time, and Owen et al. (2015) linked administrative registers to create a single statistical population dataset. The classical approach pioneered by Fellegi and Sunter (1969), which is the most popular method of RL in practice, has been successfully employed for these applications.

The probabilistic decision rule of Fellegi and Sunter (1969) is based on the likelihood ratio test idea, by which we can determine how likely a particular record pair is a true match. In applying the likelihood ratio test idea, one needs to estimate the model parameters of the underlying model and determine the thresholds of the decision rule. Winkler (1988) and Jaro (1989) treat the matching status as an unobserved variable and propose an EM algorithm for parameter estimation, which we shall refer to as the WJ-procedure. See Herzog et al. (2007), Christen (2012) and Binette and Steorts (2020) for overviews. However, as explained in Section 2, to motivate the WJ-procedure as an EM algorithm requires the crucial assumption that measures of agreement between the record pairs, called comparison vectors, are independent from one record pair to another, which is impossible to hold in reality. Newcombe et al. (1959) address dependence between comparison vectors through data application. Also, see e.g. Tancredi and Liseo (2011), Sadinle (2017), and Binette and Steorts (2020) for discussions of this issue. Bayesian approaches to RL are also available in the literature (Steorts, 2015; Sadinle, 2017; Stringham, 2021). Bayesian approaches to RL problems allow us to quantify uncertainty on the matching decisions. However, the stochastic search using MCMC algorithm in the Bayesian approach involves extra computational burden.

To develop an alternative approach, we first note that the RL problem is essentially a classification problem, where each record pair is classified into either “match” or “non-match” class. Various classification techniques based on machine learning approaches have been employed for record linkage (Hand and Christen, 2018; Christen, 2012, 2008; Sarawagi and Bhamidipaty, 2002). In this paper, we adapt the maximum entropy method for classification to record linkage. Specifically, we can view the likelihood ratio of the method proposed by Fellegi and Sunter (1969) as a special case of the density ratio and apply the maximum entropy method for density ratio estimation. For example, Nigam et al. (1999) use the maximum entropy for text classification and Nguyen et al. (2010) develop a more unified theory of maximum entropy method for density ratio estimation. There is, however, a key difference of record linkage to the standard setting of classification problems, in that the different record pairs are not distinct ‘units’ because the same record is part of many record pairs.

We present our maximum entropy record linkage algorithm for both supervised and unsupervised settings, while our main contributions concern the unsupervised case. Supervised approaches need training data, i.e., record pairs with known true match and true non-match status. Such training data are often not available in real world situations, or have to be prepared manually, which is very expensive and time-consuming (Christen, 2007). Thus, the unsupervised case is by far the most common in practice. In the unsupervised case, however, one cannot estimate the density ratio directly based on the observed true matches and non-matches, and it is troublesome to jointly model for the unobserved match status and the observed comparison scores over all the record pairs. We develop a new iterative algorithm to jointly estimate the density ratio as well as the maximum entropy classification set in the unsupervised setting and prove its convergence. The associated measures of the linkage uncertainty are also developed.

Furthermore, we show that the WJ-procedure can be incorporated as a special case of our approach to estimation, but without the need of the independence assumption between the record pairs. This reveals that the WJ-procedure can be motivated without the independence assumption, and explains why it gives reasonable results in many situations. The choice of the set of links is guided by the uncertainty measures developed in this paper. This is an important practical improvement over the classical approach, which does not directly provide any uncertainty measure for the final set of links. Our procedure is fully automatic, without the need for resource-demanding clerical review that is required under the classical approach.

The paper is organised as follows. In Section 2, the basic setup and the classical approach are introduced. In Section 3, the proposed method is developed under the setting of supervised record linkage. In Section 4, we extend the proposed method to the more challenging case of the unsupervised record linkage. Discussions of some related estimation approaches and technical details are presented in Section 5 and Appendix. Results from an extensive simulation study are presented in Section 6. Some concluding remarks and comments on further works are given in Section 7.

[Problem-I] Record linkage is not a direct application of the LRT, because one needs to evaluate all the pairs in ΩΩ\Omega instead of any given pair. 3 Maximum entropy classification: Supervised

3.2 MEC sets for record linkage

4 MEC for unsupervised record linkage

Let 𝒛𝒛\bm{z} be the K𝐾K-vector of key variables, which may be imperfect for two reasons: it is not rich enough if the true 𝒛𝒛\bm{z}-values are not unique for each distinct entity underlying the two files to be linked, or it may be subjected to errors if the observed 𝒛𝒛\bm{z} is not equal to its true value. Let A𝐴A contain only the distinct 𝒛𝒛\bm{z}-vectors from the first file, after removing any other record that has a duplicated 𝒛𝒛\bm{z}-vector to some record that is retained in A𝐴A. In other words, if the first file initially contains two or more records with exactly the same value of the combined key, then only one of them will be retained in A𝐴A for record linkage to the second file. Similarly let B𝐵B contain the unique records from the second file. The reason for separate deduplication of keys is that no comparisons between the two files can distinguish among the duplicated 𝒛𝒛\bm{z} in either file, which is an issue to be resolved otherwise.

Given A𝐴A and B𝐵B preprocessed as above, the maximal MEC set M1subscript𝑀1M_{1} only consists of the record pairs with the perfect agreement of all the key variables. For probabilistic linkage beyond M1subscript𝑀1M_{1}, one can follow the same scheme of MEC in the supervised setting, as long as one is able to obtain an estimate of the probability ratio, given which one can form the MEC set of any chosen size. Nevertheless, to estimate the associated FLR (7) and MMR (8), an estimate of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} is also needed.

4.2 Error rates

MEC for record linkage should generally be guided by the error rates, FLR and MMR, without being restricted to the estimate of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M}.

Note that {g^a​b:(a,b)∈M^}conditional-setsubscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏𝑎𝑏^𝑀\{\hat{g}_{ab}:(a,b)\in\hat{M}\} of any MEC set M^^𝑀\hat{M} are among the largest ones over ΩΩ\Omega, because MEC follows the descending order of r^a​bsubscript^𝑟𝑎𝑏\hat{r}_{ab}, except for necessary deduplication when there are multiple pairs involving a given record. To exercise greater control of the FLR, let ψ𝜓\psi be the target FLR, and consider the following bisection procedure.

  • i.

    Choose a threshold value cψsubscript𝑐𝜓c_{\psi} and form the corresponding MEC set M^​(cψ)^𝑀subscript𝑐𝜓\hat{M}(c_{\psi}), where r^a​b≥cψsubscript^𝑟𝑎𝑏subscript𝑐𝜓\hat{r}_{ab}\geq c_{\psi} for any (a,b)∈M^​(cψ)𝑎𝑏^𝑀subscript𝑐𝜓(a,b)\in\hat{M}(c_{\psi}).

  • ii.

    Calculate the estimated FLR of the resulting MEC set M^^𝑀\hat{M} as

    ψ^=1|M^|​∑(a,b)∈M^(1−g^a​b).^𝜓1^𝑀subscript𝑎𝑏^𝑀1subscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏\hat{\psi}=\frac{1}{|\hat{M}|}\sum_{(a,b)\in\hat{M}}(1-\hat{g}_{ab}). (16)

    If ψ^>ψ^𝜓𝜓\hat{\psi}>\psi, then increase cψsubscript𝑐𝜓c_{\psi}; if ψ^<ψ^𝜓𝜓\hat{\psi}<\psi, then reduce cψsubscript𝑐𝜓c_{\psi}.

Iteration between the two steps would eventually lead to a value of cψsubscript𝑐𝜓c_{\psi} that makes ψ^^𝜓\hat{\psi} as close as possible to ψ𝜓\psi, for the given probability ratio r^​(𝜸)^𝑟𝜸\hat{r}(\bm{\gamma}).

In Section 6.2, we investigate the performance of the MEC sets guided by the error rates through simulations.

5 Discussion

Below we discuss and compare two other approaches in the unsupervised setting, including the ways by which some of their elements can be incorporated into the MEC approach. Other less practical approaches are discussed in Appendix C.

5.1 The classical approach

Recall Problems I and II of the classical approach mentioned in Section 2.

From a practical point of view, Problem I can be dealt with by any deduplication method of the set M∗superscript𝑀M^{*} of classified records pairs, where r^​(𝜸a​b)^𝑟subscript𝜸𝑎𝑏\hat{r}(\bm{\gamma}_{ab}) is above a threshold value for all (a,b)∈M∗𝑎𝑏superscript𝑀(a,b)\in M^{*}. As “an advance over previous ad hoc assignment methods”, Jaro (1989) chooses the linked set M^∗⊆M∗superscript^𝑀superscript𝑀\hat{M}^{*}\subseteq M^{*}, which maximises the sum of log⁡r^​(𝜸a​b)^𝑟subscript𝜸𝑎𝑏\log\hat{r}(\bm{\gamma}_{ab}) subject to the constraint of one-one link. Since g^a​bsubscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏\hat{g}_{ab} is a monotonic function of r^​(𝜸a​b)^𝑟subscript𝜸𝑎𝑏\hat{r}(\bm{\gamma}_{ab}), this amounts to choose M^∗superscript^𝑀\hat{M}^{*} which maximises the expected number of matches in it, denoted by

nM∗=∑(a,b)∈M^∗g^a​bsuperscriptsubscript𝑛𝑀subscript𝑎𝑏superscript^𝑀subscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏n_{M}^{*}=\sum_{(a,b)\in\hat{M}^{*}}\hat{g}_{ab}

But nM∗superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M}^{*} is still not connected to the probabilities of false links and non-links defined by (1). As illustrated below, neither does it directly control the errors of the linked M^∗superscript^𝑀\hat{M}^{*}.

Consider linking two files with 100 records each. Suppose Jaro’s assignment method yields |M^∗|=100superscript^𝑀100|\hat{M}^{*}|=100 on one occasion, where 80 links have g^a​b≈1subscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏1\hat{g}_{ab}\approx 1 and 20 links have g^a​b≈0.75subscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏0.75\hat{g}_{ab}\approx 0.75, such that nM∗≈95superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑀95n_{M}^{*}\approx 95. Suppose it yields 90 links with g^a​b≈1subscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏1\hat{g}_{ab}\approx 1 and 10 links with g^a​b≈0.5subscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏0.5\hat{g}_{ab}\approx 0.5 on another occasion, where nM∗≈95superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑀95n_{M}^{*}\approx 95. Clearly, nM∗superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M}^{*} does not directly control the linkage errors in M^∗superscript^𝑀\hat{M}^{*}. Moreover, there is no compelling reason to accept 100 links on both these occasions, simply because 100 one-one links are possible.

In forming the MEC set one deals with Problem I directly, based on the concept of maximum entropy that has relevance in many areas of scientific investigation. The implementation is simple and fast for large datasets. The estimated error rates FLR (16) and MMR in (17) are directly defined for a given MEC set.

Problem II concerns the parameter estimation. As explained earlier, applying the EM algorithm based on the objective function (2) proposed by Winkler (1988) and Jaro (1989) is not a valid approach of maximum likelihood estimation (MLE). One may easily compare this WJ-procedure to that given in Section 4.1, where both adopt the same model (5) and the same estimator of u​(𝜸;𝝃)𝑢𝜸𝝃u(\bm{\gamma};\bm{\xi}) via ξ^ksubscript^𝜉𝑘\hat{\xi}_{k} given by (15). It is then clear that the same formula is used for updating nM(t)superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑀𝑡n_{M}^{(t)} at each iteration, but a different formula is used for

θk(t)=1nM(t)​∑(a,b)∈Ωg^a​b(t)​γa​b,ksuperscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡1superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑀𝑡subscript𝑎𝑏Ωsuperscriptsubscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏𝑡subscript𝛾𝑎𝑏𝑘\theta_{k}^{(t)}=\frac{1}{{n}_{M}^{(t)}}\sum_{(a,b)\in\Omega}\hat{g}_{ab}^{(t)}\gamma_{ab,k} (18)

where the numerator is derived from all the pairs in ΩΩ\Omega, whereas θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)} given by (13) uses only the pairs in the MEC set M(t)superscript𝑀𝑡M^{(t)}. Notice that the two differ only in the unsupervised setting, but they would become the same in the supervised setting, where one can use the observed binary ga​bsubscript𝑔𝑎𝑏g_{ab} instead of the estimated fractional g^a​bsubscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏\hat{g}_{ab}.

Thus, one may incorporate the WJ-procedure as a variation of the unsupervised MEC algorithm, where the formulae (18) and (15) are chosen specifically. This is the reason why it can give reasonable parameter estimates in many situations, despite its misconception as the MLE. Simulations will be used later to compare empirically the two formulae (13) and (18) for θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)}.

6 Simulation Study

6.1 Set-up

To explore the practical feasibility of the unsupervised MEC algorithm for record linkage, we conduct a simulation study based on the data sets listed in Table 2, which are disseminated by ESSnet-DI (McLeod et al., 2011) and freely available online. Each record in a data set has associated synthetic key variables, which may be distorted by missing values and typos when they are created, in ways that imitate real-life errors (McLeod et al., 2011).

We consider the linkage keys forename, surname, sex, and date of birth (DOB). To model the key variables, we divide DOB into 3 key variables (Day, Month, Year). For text variables such as forename and surname, we divide them into 4 key variables by using the Soundex coding algorithm (Copas and Hilton, 1990, p. 290), which reduces a name to a code consisting of the leading letter followed by three digits, e.g. Copas ≡\equiv C120, Hilton ≡\equiv H435. The twelve key variables for record linkage are presented in Table 3.

We set up two scenarios to generate linkage files. We use the unique identification variable (PERSON-ID) for sampling, which are available in all the three data sets. We sample nA=500subscript𝑛𝐴500n_{A}=500 and nB=1000subscript𝑛𝐵1000n_{B}=1000 individuals from PRD and CIS, respectively. Let pAsubscript𝑝𝐴p_{A} be the proportion of records in the smaller file (PRD) that are also selected in the larger file (CIS), by which we can vary the degree of overlap, i.e. the set of matched individuals A​B𝐴𝐵AB, between A𝐴A and B𝐵B. We use pA=0.8,0.5subscript𝑝𝐴0.80.5p_{A}=0.8,0.5 or 0.30.30.3 under either scenario.

6.2 Results: Estimation

For the unsupervised MEC algorithm given in Section 4.1, one can adopt (13) or (18) for updating θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)}. Moreover, one can use (15) for ξ^ksubscript^𝜉𝑘\hat{\xi}_{k} directly, or (20) for updating ξk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜉𝑘𝑡\xi_{k}^{(t)} iteratively. In particular, choosing (18) and (15) effectively incorporates the procedure of Winkler (1988) and Jaro (1989) for parameter estimation. Note that the MEC approach still differs to that of Jaro (1989), with respect to the formation of the linked set M^^𝑀\hat{M}.

Table 4 compares the performance of the unsupervised MEC algorithm, using different formulae for θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)} and ξk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜉𝑘𝑡\xi_{k}^{(t)}, where the size of M^^𝑀\hat{M} is equal to the corresponding estimate n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M}. In addition, we include θ^k=nM​(1;k)/nMsubscript^𝜃𝑘subscript𝑛𝑀1𝑘subscript𝑛𝑀\hat{\theta}_{k}=n_{M}(1;k)/n_{M} estimated directly from the matched pairs in M𝑀M, as if M𝑀M were available for supervised learning, together with (15) for ξ^ksubscript^𝜉𝑘\hat{\xi}_{k}. The true parameters and error rates are given in addition to their estimates.

As expected, the best results are obtained when the parameter θksubscript𝜃𝑘\theta_{k} is estimated directly from the matched pairs in M𝑀M, i.e., θ^k=nM​(1;k)/nMsubscript^𝜃𝑘subscript𝑛𝑀1𝑘subscript𝑛𝑀\hat{\theta}_{k}=n_{M}(1;k)/n_{M}, together with (15) for ξ^ksubscript^𝜉𝑘\hat{\xi}_{k}, despite ξ^ksubscript^𝜉𝑘\hat{\xi}_{k} by (15) is not exactly unbiased. Nevertheless, the approximate estimator ξ^ksubscript^𝜉𝑘\hat{\xi}_{k} can be improved, since the profile-EM estimator given by (20) is seen to perform better across all the set-ups, where both are combined with (13) for θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)}. When it comes to the two formulae of θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)} by (13) and (18), and the resulting nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M}-estimators and the error rates FLR and MMR, we notice the followings.

  • •

    Scenario-I: When the size of the matched set M𝑀M is relatively large at pA=0.8subscript𝑝𝐴0.8p_{A}=0.8 , there are only small differences in terms of the average and median of the two estimators of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M}, and the difference is just a couple of false links in terms of the linkage errors. Figures 1 shows that (13) results in a few larger errors of n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M} than (18) over the 200 simulations, when pA=0.8subscript𝑝𝐴0.8p_{A}=0.8 or π=0.0008𝜋0.0008\pi=0.0008. As the size of the matched set M𝑀M decreases, the averages and medians of the estimators of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} resulting from (13) and (20) are closer to the true values than those of the other estimators. Especially when the matched set M𝑀M is relatively small, where π=0.0003𝜋0.0003\pi=0.0003, the formula (18) results in considerably worse estimation of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} in every respect. While this is partly due to the use of (15) instead of (20), most of the difference is down to the choice of θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)}, which can be seen from intermediary comparisons to the results based on (13) and (15).

  • •

    Scenario-II: The use of (13) and (20) for the unsupervised MEC algorithm performs better than using the other formulae in terms of both estimation of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} and error rates across the three sizes of the matched set (Figure 2). Relatively greater improvement is achieved by using (13) and (20) for the smaller matched sets.

The results suggest that the unsupervised MEC algorithm tends to be more affected by the size of the matched set under Scenario-I than Scenario-II. Choosing (13) and (20), however, seems to yield the most robust estimation of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} and error rates against the small size of the matched set M𝑀M, regardless the informativeness of key-variable errors. The reason must be the fact that the numerator of θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)} is calculated in (18) over all the pairs in ΩΩ\Omega instead of the MEC set M(t)superscript𝑀𝑡M^{(t)}, which seems more sensitive when the imbalance between M𝑀M and U𝑈U is aggravated, while the sizes of A𝐴A and B𝐵B remain fixed.

We also include the additional results obtained for pA=0.2,0.15,subscript𝑝𝐴0.20.15p_{A}=0.2,0.15, and 0.10.10.1 in Appendix D. The estimate n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M} (or π^^𝜋\hat{\pi}) gets worse as pAsubscript𝑝𝐴p_{A} (or π𝜋\pi) reduces, which is consistent with the previous findings of others, for example, Enamorado et al. (2019) showed that a greater degree of overlap between data sets leads to better merging results in terms of the error rates as well as the accuracy of their estimates. The problem is also highlighted by Sadinle (2017). Record linkage in cases of extremely low prevalence of true matches is a problem that needs to be studied more carefully on its own.

6.3 Results: MEC set

Aiming the MEC set M^^𝑀\hat{M} at the estimated size n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M} is generally not a reasonable approach to record linkage. Record linkage should be guided directly by the associated uncertainty, i.e. the error rates FLR and MMR, based on their estimates (16) and (17), as described in Section 4.2. Note that this does require the estimation of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} in addition to r​(𝜸)𝑟𝜸r(\bm{\gamma}).

We have FLR^=MMR^^FLR^MMR\widehat{\mbox{FLR}}=\widehat{\mbox{MMR}} in Table 4, because |M^|=n^M^𝑀subscript^𝑛𝑀|\hat{M}|=\hat{n}_{M} here. It can be seen that these follow the true FLR more closely than the MMR, especially when n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M} is estimated using the formulae (13) and (20). This is hardly surprising. Take e.g. the maximal MEC set M1subscript𝑀1M_{1} that consists of the pairs whose key variables agree completely and uniquely. Provided reasonably rich key variables, as the setting here, one can expect the FLR of M1subscript𝑀1M_{1} to be low, such that even a naïve estimate FLR^=0^FLR0\widehat{\mbox{FLR}}=0 probably does not err much. Meanwhile, the true MMR has a much wider range from one application to another, because the difference between nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} and |M1|subscript𝑀1|M_{1}| is determined by the extent of key-variable errors, such that the estimate of MMR depends more critically on that of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M}. The situation is similar for any MEC set beyond M1subscript𝑀1M_{1}, as long as g^a​bsubscript^𝑔𝑎𝑏\hat{g}_{ab} remains very high for any (a,b)∈M^𝑎𝑏^𝑀(a,b)\in\hat{M}.

We use only (13) for θk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜃𝑘𝑡\theta_{k}^{(t)} and (20) for ξk(t)superscriptsubscript𝜉𝑘𝑡\xi_{k}^{(t)} to obtain the corresponding n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M}. In other words, the fact that |M^|^𝑀|\hat{M}| differs to the estimate n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M} is not necessarily a cause of concern for the MEC algorithm guided by targeting the FLR.

To estimate the MMR by (17), one can either use |M^|^𝑀|\hat{M}| as the estimate of nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M}, or one can use n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M} from parameter estimation based on (13) and (20). In the former case, one would obtain MMR^=FLR^^MMR^FLR\widehat{\mbox{MMR}}=\widehat{\mbox{FLR}}. While this MMR^^MMR\widehat{\mbox{MMR}} is not unreasonable in absolute terms since |M^|^𝑀|\hat{M}| is close to nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} here, as can be seen from comparing the mean of FLR^^FLR\widehat{\mbox{FLR}} with that of the true MMR in Table 5, it has a drawback a priori, in that it decreases as the target FLR decreases, although one is likely to miss out on more true matches when more links are excluded from the MEC set M^^𝑀\hat{M}. Using n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M} from parameter estimation directly makes sense in this respect, since the true nMsubscript𝑛𝑀n_{M} must remain the same, regardless the target FLR. However, the estimator MMR^^MMR\widehat{\mbox{MMR}} could then become less reliable given relatively low prevalence π𝜋\pi, where n^Msubscript^𝑛𝑀\hat{n}_{M} could be sensitive in such situations.

In short, the estimation of FLR tends to be more reliable than that of MMR, especially if the prevalence π𝜋\pi is relatively low in its theoretical range 0<π≤min⁡(nA,nB)/n0𝜋subscript𝑛𝐴subscript𝑛𝐵𝑛0<\pi\leq\min(n_{A},n_{B})/n. The following recommendations for unsupervised record linkage seem warranted.

  • •

    When forming the MEC set M^^𝑀\hat{M} according to the uncertainty of linkage, it is more robust to rely on the FLR, estimated by (16).

  • •

7 Final remarks

We have developed an approach of maximum entropy classification to record linkage. This provides a unified probabilistic record linkage framework both in the supervised and unsupervised settings, where a coherent classification set of links are chosen explicitly with respect to the associated uncertainty. The theoretical formulation overcomes some persistent flaws of the classical approaches. Furthermore, the proposed MEC algorithm is fully automatic, unlike the classical approach that generally requires clerical review to resolve the undecided cases.

An important issue that is worth further research concerns the estimation of relevant parameters in the model of key-variable errors that cause problems for record linkage. First, as pointed out earlier, treating record linkage as a classification problem allows one to explore many modern machine learning techniques. A key challenge in this respect is the fact that the different record pairs are not distinct ‘units’, such that any powerful supervised learning technique needs to be adapted to the unsupervised setting, where it is impossible to estimate the relevant parameters based on the true matches and non-matches, including the number of matched entities. Next, the model of the key-variable errors or the comparison scores can be refined. Once these issues are resolved together, further improvements on the parameter estimation can be hopefully made, which will benefit both the classification of the set of links and the assessment of the associated uncertainty.

Another issue that is interesting to explore in practice is the various possible forms of informative key-variable errors, insofar as the model pertaining to the matched entities in one way or another differs to that of the unmatched entities. Suitable variations of the MEC approach may need to be configured in different situations.
